# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: real-time-linux-preempt
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/interrupt-latency] In computing, **interrupt latency** refers to the delay between the start of an Interrupt Request (IRQ) and the start of the respective Interrupt Service Routine (ISR).
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/interrupt-latency] For many operating systems, devices are serviced as soon as the device's interrupt handler is executed.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/interrupt-latency] Interrupt latency may be affected by microprocessor design, interrupt controllers, interrupt masking, and the operating system's (OS) interrupt handling methods.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/interrupt-latency] There is usually a trade-off between interrupt latency, throughput, and processor utilization.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/interrupt-latency] Many of the techniques of CPU and OS design that improve interrupt latency will decrease throughput and increase processor utilization.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/interrupt-latency] Techniques that increase throughput may increase interrupt latency and increase processor utilization.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/interrupt-latency] Lastly, trying to reduce processor utilization may increase interrupt latency and decrease throughput.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/interrupt-latency] Minimum interrupt latency is largely determined by the interrupt controller circuit and its configuration.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/interrupt-latency] They can also affect the jitter in the interrupt latency, which can drastically affect the real-time schedulability of the system.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/interrupt-latency] The Intel APIC architecture is well known for producing a huge amount of interrupt latency jitter.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/interrupt-latency] Maximum interrupt latency is largely determined by the methods an OS uses for interrupt handling.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/interrupt-latency] For example, most processors allow programs to disable interrupts, putting off the execution of interrupt handlers, in order to protect critical sections of code.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/interrupt-latency] During the execution of such a critical section, all interrupt handlers that cannot execute safely within a critical section are blocked (they save the minimum amount of information required to restart the interrupt handler after all critical sections have exited).
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/interrupt-latency] So the interrupt latency for a blocked interrupt is extended to the end of the critical section, plus any interrupts with equal and higher priority that arrived while the block was in place.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/interrupt-latency] Many computer systems require low interrupt latencies, especially embedded systems that need to control machinery in real-time.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/interrupt-latency] Sometimes these systems use a real-time operating system (RTOS).
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/interrupt-latency] An RTOS makes the promise that no more than a specified maximum amount of time will pass between executions of subroutines.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/interrupt-latency] In order to do this, the RTOS must also guarantee that interrupt latency will never exceed a predefined maximum.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/interrupt-latency] Advanced interrupt controllers implement a multitude of hardware features in order to minimize the overhead during context switches and the effective interrupt latency.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/interrupt-latency] Also, there are many other methods hardware may use to help lower the requirements for shorter interrupt latency in order to make a given interrupt latency tolerable in a situation.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/interrupt-latency] These include buffers, and flow control.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/interrupt-latency] For example, most network cards implement transmit and receive ring buffers, interrupt rate limiting, and hardware flow control.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/interrupt-latency] Buffers allow data to be stored until it can be transferred, and flow control allows the network card to pause communications without having to discard data if the buffer is full.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/interrupt-latency] Modern hardware also implements interrupt rate limiting.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/interrupt-latency] This helps prevent interrupt storms or live-locks by having the hardware wait a programmable minimum amount of time between each interrupt it generates.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/interrupt-latency] Interrupt rate limiting reduces the amount of time spent servicing interrupts, allowing the processor to spend more time doing useful work.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/interrupt-latency] Exceeding this time results in a soft (recoverable) or hard (non-recoverable) error.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] The **Linux kernel** is a free and open-source Unix-like kernel that is used in many computer systems worldwide.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] The kernel was created by Linus Torvalds in 1991 and was soon adopted as the kernel for the GNU operating system (OS), which was created to be a free replacement for Unix.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Since the late 1990s, it has been included in many operating system distributions, many of which are called Linux.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] One such Linux kernel operating system is Android, which is used in many mobile and embedded devices.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Most of the kernel code is written in C as supported by the GNU Compiler Collection (GCC), which has extensions beyond standard C.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] The code also contains assembly code for architecture-specific logic such as optimizing memory use and task execution.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] The kernel has a modular design such that modules can be integrated as software components – including dynamically loaded.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] The kernel is monolithic in an architectural sense since the entire OS kernel runs in kernel space.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Linux is provided under the GNU General Public License version 2, although it contains files under other compatible licenses.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] In 1991, Linus Torvalds was a computer science student enrolled at the University of Helsinki.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] During his time there, he began to develop an operating system as a side-project inspired by UNIX, for a personal computer.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] He started with a task switcher in Intel 80386 assembly language and a terminal driver.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] On 17 September 1991, Torvalds prepared version 0.01 of Linux and put on the "ftp.funet.fi" – FTP server of the Finnish University and Research Network (FUNET).
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] It was not even executable since its code still needed Minix to compile and test it.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] On 5 October 1991, Torvalds announced the first "official" version of Linux, version 0.02.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] At the time, the GNU Project had completed many components for its free UNIX replacement, GNU, but its kernel, the GNU Hurd, was incomplete.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] The project adopted the Linux kernel for its OS.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Torvalds labeled the kernel with major version 0 to indicate that it was not yet intended for general use.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Version 0.11, released in December 1991, was the first version to be self-hosted; compiled on a computer running the Linux kernel.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] When Torvalds released version 0.12 in January 1992, he adopted the GNU General Public License version 2 (GPLv2) over his previous self-drafted license, which had not permitted commercial redistribution.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] In contrast to Unix, all Linux source files are freely available, including device drivers.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] The initial success of Linux was driven by programmers and testers across the world.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Because Linux implemented Unix-like system call semantics and exposed the standard POSIX APIs through an implementation of the C standard library, Linux could run software and applications that had been originally developed for Unix.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] On 19 January 1992, the first post to the new newsgroup *alt.os.linux* was submitted.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] On 31 March 1992, the newsgroup was renamed *comp.os.linux*.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] The fact that Linux is a monolithic kernel rather than a microkernel was the topic of a debate between Andrew S.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Tanenbaum, the creator of MINIX, and Torvalds.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] The Tanenbaum–Torvalds debate started in 1992 on the Usenet group *comp.os.minix* as a general discussion about kernel architectures.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Version 0.96 released in May 1992 was the first capable of running the X Window System.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] In March 1994, Linux 1.0.0 was released with 176,250 lines of code.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] As indicated by the version number, it was the first version considered suitable for a production environment.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] In June 1996, after release 1.3, Torvalds decided that Linux had evolved enough to warrant a new major number, and so labeled the next release as version 2.0.0.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Significant features of 2.0 included symmetric multiprocessing (SMP), support for more processors types and support for selecting specific hardware targets and for enabling architecture-specific features and optimizations.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] The *make *config* family of commands of *kbuild* enable and configure options for building ad hoc kernel executables (vmlinux) and loadable modules.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Version 2.2, released on 20 January 1999, improved locking granularity and SMP management, added m68k, PowerPC, Sparc64, Alpha, and other 64-bit platforms support.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Furthermore, it added new file systems including Microsoft's NTFS read-only capability.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] In 1999, IBM published its patches to the Linux 2.2.13 code for the support of the S/390 architecture.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Version 2.4.0, released on 4 January 2001, contained support for ISA Plug and Play, USB, and PC Cards.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Linux 2.4 added support for the Pentium 4 and Itanium (the latter introduced the ia64 ISA that was jointly developed by Intel and Hewlett-Packard to supersede the older PA-RISC), and for the newer 64-bit MIPS processor.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Development for 2.4.*x* changed a bit in that more features were made available throughout the series, including support for Bluetooth, Logical Volume Manager (LVM) version 1, RAID support, InterMezzo and ext3 file systems.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Version 2.6.0 was released on 17 December 2003.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] The development for 2.6.*x* changed further towards including new features throughout the series.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Starting with 2.6.x releases, the kernel supported a large number of file systems.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Some were designed for Linux, like ext3, ext4, FUSE, and Btrfs.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Others were native to other operating systems like JFS, XFS, Minix, Xenix, Irix, Solaris, System V, Windows, and MS-DOS.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Though development had not used a version control system thus far, in 2002, Linux developers adopted BitKeeper, which was made freely available to them even though it was not free software.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] In 2005, because of efforts to reverse-engineer it, the company that owned the software revoked its support of the Linux community.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] In response, Torvalds and others wrote Git.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] The new system was written within weeks, and in two months the first official kernel made using it was released.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] In 2005 the *stable team* was formed as a response to the lack of a kernel tree where people could work on bug fixes, and it would keep updating *stable* versions.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] In February 2008 the *linux-next* tree was created to serve as a place where patches aimed to be merged during the next development cycle gathered.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Several subsystem maintainers also adopted the suffix *-next* for trees containing code that they mean to submit for inclusion in the next release cycle.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] As of January 2014, the in-development version of Linux is held in an unstable branch named *linux-next*.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] The 20th anniversary of Linux was celebrated by Torvalds in July 2011 with the release of version 3.0.0.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] As 2.6 had been the version number for 8 years, a new *uname26* personality that reports 3.x as 2.6.40+x had to be added to the kernel so that old programs would work.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Version 3.0 was released on 22 July 2011.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] On 30 May 2011, Torvalds announced that the big change was "NOTHING.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Absolutely nothing." and asked, "...let's make sure we really make the next release not just an all new shiny number, but a good kernel too." After the expected 6–7 weeks of the development process, it would be released near the 20th anniversary of Linux.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] The same series unified support for the ARM processor.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] The numbering change from 2.6.39 to 3.0, and from 3.19 to 4.0, involved no meaningful technical differentiation; the major version number was increased simply to avoid large minor numbers.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Stable 3.x.y kernels were released until 3.19 in February 2015.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Version 3.11, released on 2 September 2013, added many new features such as the new O_TMPFILE flag for `open(2)` to reduce temporary file vulnerabilities, experimental AMD Radeon dynamic power management, low-latency network polling, and zswap (compressed swap cache).
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] In April 2015, Torvalds released kernel version 4.0.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] By February 2015, Linux had received contributions from nearly 12,000 programmers from more than 1,200 companies, including some of the world's largest software and hardware vendors.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Version 4.1 of Linux, released in June 2015, contains over 19.5 million lines of code contributed by almost 14,000 programmers.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] A total of 1,991 developers, of whom 334 were first-time collaborators, added more than 553,000 lines of code to version 5.8, breaking the record previously held by version 4.9.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] According to the Stack Overflow's annual Developer Survey of 2019, more than 53% of all respondents have developed software for Linux and about 27% for Android, although only about 25% develop with Linux-based operating systems.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Most websites run on Linux-based operating systems, and all of the world's 500 most powerful supercomputers run on Linux.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Linux distributions bundle the kernel with system software (e.g., the GNU C Library, systemd, and other Unix utilities and daemons) and a wide selection of application software, but their usage share in desktops is low in comparison to other operating systems.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Android, which runs on a modified Linux kernel, accounts for the majority of mobile device operating systems, and is increasingly being used in embedded devices, making it a significant driver of Linux adoption.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] The cost to redevelop version 2.6.0 of the Linux kernel in a traditional proprietary development setting has been estimated to be US$612 million (€467M, £394M) in 2004 prices using the COCOMO person-month estimation model.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] In 2006, a study funded by the European Union put the redevelopment cost of kernel version 2.6.8 higher, at €882M ($1.14bn, £744M).
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] This topic was revisited in October 2008 by Amanda McPherson, Brian Proffitt, and Ron Hale-Evans.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Wheeler's methodology, they estimated redevelopment of the 2.6.25 kernel now costs $1.3bn (part of a total $10.8bn to redevelop Fedora 9).
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Again, Garcia-Garcia and Alonso de Magdaleno from University of Oviedo (Spain) estimate that the value annually added to kernel was about €100M between 2005 and 2007 and €225M in 2008, it would cost also more than €1bn (about $1.4bn as of February 2010) to develop in the European Union.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] As of 7 March 2011, using then-current LOC (lines of code) of a 2.6.x Linux kernel and wage numbers with David A.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Wheeler's calculations it would cost approximately $3bn (about €2.2bn) to redevelop the Linux kernel as it keeps getting bigger.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] An updated calculation as of 26 September 2018, using then-current 20,088,609 LOC (lines of code) for the 4.14.14 Linux kernel and the current US national average programmer salary of $75,506 show that it would cost approximately $14,725,449,000 (£11,191,341,000) to rewrite the existing code.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Most who use Linux do so via a Linux distribution.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Some distributions ship the vanilla or stable kernel.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Several vendors (such as Red Hat and Debian) maintain a customized source tree.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Graph of the sizes of Linux Kernel versions in millions of lines of code.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] The community of Linux kernel developers comprises about 5000–6000 members.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] According to the "2017 State of Linux Kernel Development", a study issued by the Linux Foundation, covering the commits for the releases 4.8 to 4.13, about 1500 developers were contributing from about 200–250 companies on average.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] The top 30 developers contributed a little more than 16% of the code.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] For companies, the top contributors are Intel (13.1%) and Red Hat (7.2%), Linaro (5.6%), IBM (4.1%), the second and fifth places are held by the 'none' (8.2%) and 'unknown' (4.1%) categories.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Prominent Linux kernel developers have been aware of the importance of avoiding conflicts between developers.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] For a long time there was no code of conduct for kernel developers due to opposition by Torvalds.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] A Linux Kernel *Code of Conflict* was introduced on 8 March 2015.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] It was replaced on 16 September 2018 by a new *Code of Conduct* based on the Contributor Covenant.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] This coincided with a public apology by Torvalds and a brief break from kernel development.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] On 30 November 2018, complying with the *Code of Conduct*, Jarkko Sakkinen of Intel sent out patches replacing instances of "fuck" appearing in source code comments with suitable versions focused on the word 'hug'.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Developers who feel treated unfairly can report this to the Linux Foundation Technical Advisory Board.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] In July 2013, the maintainer of the USB 3.0 driver Sage Sharp asked Torvalds to address the abusive commentary in the kernel development community.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] In 2014, Sharp backed out of Linux kernel development, saying that "The focus on technical excellence, in combination with overloaded maintainers, and people with different cultural and social norms, means that Linux kernel maintainers are often blunt, rude, or brutal to get their job done".
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] At the linux.conf.au (LCA) conference in 2018, developers expressed the view that the culture of the community has gotten much better in the past few years.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Daniel Vetter, the maintainer of the Intel drm/i915 graphics kernel driver, commented that the "rather violent language and discussion" in the kernel community has decreased or disappeared.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Laurent Pinchart asked developers for feedback on their experiences with the kernel community at the 2017 Embedded Linux Conference Europe.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] The issues brought up were discussed a few days later at the Maintainers Summit.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Concerns over the lack of consistency in how maintainers responded to patches submitted by developers were echoed by Shuah Khan, the maintainer of the kernel self-test framework.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Torvalds contended that there would never be consistency in the handling of patches because different kernel subsystems have, over time, adopted different development processes.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Therefore, it was agreed upon that each kernel subsystem maintainer would document the rules for patch acceptance.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] The kernel source code, a.k.a. source tree, is managed in the Git version control system – also created by Torvalds.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] As of 2021, the 5.11 release of the Linux kernel had around 30.34 million lines of code.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Roughly 14% of the code is part of the "core," including architecture-specific code, kernel code, and memory management code, while 60% is drivers.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Contributions are submitted as patches, in the form of text messages on the Linux kernel mailing list (LKML) (and often also on other mailing lists dedicated to particular subsystems).
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] The patches must conform to a set of rules and to a formal language that, among other things, describes which lines of code are to be deleted and what others are to be added to the specified files.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] These patches can be automatically processed so that system administrators can apply them in order to make just some changes to the code or to incrementally upgrade to the next version.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Linux is distributed also in GNU zip (gzip) and bzip2 formats.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] A developer who wants to change the Linux kernel writes and tests a code change.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Depending on how significant the change is and how many subsystems it modifies, the change will either be submitted as a single patch or in multiple patches of source code.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] In case of a single subsystem that is maintained by a single maintainer, these patches are sent as e-mails to the maintainer of the subsystem with the appropriate mailing list in Cc.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] The maintainer and the readers of the mailing list will review the patches and provide feedback.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Once the review process has finished the subsystem maintainer accepts the patches in the relevant Git kernel tree.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] If the changes to the Linux kernel are bug fixes that are considered important enough, a pull request for the patches will be sent to Torvalds within a few days.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Otherwise, a pull request will be sent to Torvalds during the next merge window.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] The merge window usually lasts two weeks and starts immediately after the release of the previous kernel version.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] The Git kernel source tree names all developers who have contributed to the Linux kernel in the *Credits* directory and all subsystem maintainers are listed in *Maintainers*.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] As with many large open-source software projects, developers are required to adhere to the Contributor Covenant, a code of conduct intended to address harassment of minority contributors.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Additionally, to prevent offense the use of inclusive terminology within the source code is mandated.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Linux is written in a special C programming language supported by GCC, a compiler that extends the C standard in many ways, for example using inline sections of code written in the assembly language (in GCC's "AT&T-style" syntax) of the target architecture.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Initial support for the Rust programming language was added in Linux 6.1, which was released in December 2022, with later kernel versions, such as Linux 6.2 and Linux 6.3, further improving the support.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] As for most software, the kernel is versioned as a series of dot-separated numbers.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] For early versions, the version consisted of three or four dot-separated numbers called *major release*, *minor release* and *revision.* At that time, odd-numbered minor releases were for development and testing, while even numbered minor releases for production.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] The optional fourth digit indicated a patch level.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Development releases were indicated with a release candidate suffix (*-rc*).
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] The current versioning conventions are different.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] The odd/even number implying dev/prod has been dropped, and a major version is indicated by the first two numbers together.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] While the time-frame is open for the development of the next major, the -rcN suffix is used to identify the n'th release candidate for the next version.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] For example, the release of the version 4.16 was preceded by seven 4.16-rcN (from -rc1 to -rc7).
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Once a stable version is released, its maintenance is passed to the *stable team*.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Updates to a stable release are identified by a three-number scheme (e.g., 4.16.1, 4.16.2, ...).
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] The kernel is usually built with the GNU toolchain.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] The GNU C compiler, GNU cc, part of the GNU Compiler Collection (GCC), is the default compiler for mainline Linux.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] The GNU Assembler (often called GAS or GNU as) outputs the object files from the GCC generated assembly code.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Finally, the GNU Linker (GNU ld) produces a statically linked executable kernel file called vmlinux.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Both as and ld are part of GNU Binary Utilities (binutils).
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] GNU cc was for a long time the only compiler capable of correctly building Linux.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] In 2004, Intel claimed to have modified the kernel so that its C compiler was also capable of compiling it.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] There was another such reported success in 2009, with a modified 2.6.22 version.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Support for the Intel compiler has been dropped in 2023.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Since 2010, effort has been underway to build Linux with Clang, an alternative compiler for the C language; as of 12 April 2014, the official kernel could almost be compiled by Clang.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] The project dedicated to this effort is named *LLVMLinux* after the LLVM compiler infrastructure upon which Clang is built.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] LLVMLinux does not aim to fork either Linux or the LLVM, therefore it is a meta-project composed of patches that are eventually submitted to the upstream projects.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] By enabling Linux to be compiled by Clang, developers may benefit from shorter compilation times.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] In 2017, developers completed upstreaming patches to support building the Linux kernel with Clang in the 4.15 release, having backported support for X86-64 and AArch64 to the 4.4, 4.9, and 4.14 branches of the stable kernel tree.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Google's Pixel 2 shipped with the first Clang built Linux kernel, though patches for Pixel (1st generation) did exist.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] 2018 saw ChromeOS move to building kernels with Clang by default, while Android made Clang and LLVM's linker LLD required for kernel builds in 2019.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Google moved its production kernel used throughout its datacenters to being built with Clang in 2020.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] The *ClangBuiltLinux* group coordinates fixes to both Linux and LLVM to ensure compatibility, both composed of members from *LLVMLinux* and having upstreamed patches from *LLVMLinux*.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] As with any software, problems with the Linux kernel can be difficult to troubleshoot.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Common challenges relate to userspace vs. kernel space access, misuse of synchronization primitives, and incorrect hardware management.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] An oops is a non-fatal error in the kernel.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] After such an error, operations continue with suspect reliability.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] A panic (generated by panic()) is a fatal error.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] After such an error, the kernel prints a message and halts the computer.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] The kernel provides for *debugging by printing* via printk(), which stores messages in a circular buffer (overwriting older entries with newer).
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] The syslog(2) system call provides for reading and clearing the message buffer and for setting the maximum *log level* of the messages to be sent to the console.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Kernel messages are also exported to userland through the */dev/kmsg* interface.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] The *ftrace* mechanism allow for debugging by tracing.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] It is used for monitoring and debugging Linux at runtime and it can analyze user space latencies due to kernel misbehavior.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Furthermore, *ftrace* allows users to trace Linux at boot-time.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] With KGDB Linux can be debugged in much the same way as userspace programs.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] KGDB requires an additional machine that runs GDB and that is connected to the target to be debugged using a serial cable or Ethernet.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] The Linux kernel project integrates new code on a rolling basis.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Standard operating procedure is that software checked into the project must work and compile without error.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Each kernel subsystem is assigned a maintainer who is responsible for reviewing patches against the kernel code standards and keeping a queue of patches that can be submitted to Torvalds within a merge window that is usually several weeks.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Patches are merged by Torvalds into the source code of the prior stable Linux kernel release, creating the release candidate (-rc) for the next stable release.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Once the merge window is closed, only fixes to the new code in the development release are accepted.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] The -rc development release of the kernel goes through regression testing and once it is considered stable by Torvalds and the subsystem maintainers, a new version is released and the development process starts over again.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] The Git tree that contains the Linux kernel source code is referred to as **mainline Linux**.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Every stable kernel release originates from the mainline tree, and is frequently published on kernel.org.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Mainline Linux has only solid support for a small subset of the many devices that run Linux.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Non-mainline support is provided by independent projects, such as Yocto or Linaro, but in many cases the kernel from the device vendor is needed.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Using a vendor kernel likely requires a board support package.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Maintaining a kernel tree outside of mainline Linux has proven to be difficult.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] The maintainer of the stable branch, Greg Kroah-Hartman, has applied the term *Linux-like* to downstream kernel forks by vendors that add millions of lines of code to the mainline kernel.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] In 2019, Google stated that it wanted to use the mainline Linux kernel in Android so the number of kernel forks would be reduced.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] The term Linux-like has also been applied to the Embeddable Linux Kernel Subset, which does not include the full mainline Linux kernel but a small modified subset of the code.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] There are certain communities that develop kernels based on the official Linux.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Some interesting bits of code from these forks that include Linux-libre, Compute Node Linux, INK, L4Linux, RTLinux, and User-Mode Linux (UML) have been merged into the mainline.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Some operating systems developed for mobile phones initially used heavily modified versions of Linux, including Google Android, Firefox OS, HP webOS, Nokia Maemo and Jolla Sailfish OS.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Today Android uses a customized Linux where major changes are implemented in device drivers, but some changes to the core kernel code is required.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Android developers also submit patches to the official Linux that finally can boot the Android operating system.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] For example, a Nexus 7 can boot and run the mainline Linux.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] The latest version and older versions are maintained separately.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Most of the latest kernel releases were supervised by Torvalds.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] The Linux kernel developer community maintains a stable kernel by applying fixes for software bugs that have been discovered during the development of the subsequent stable kernel.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Therefore, www.kernel.org always lists two stable kernels.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] The next stable Linux kernel is released about 8 to 12 weeks later.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Some releases are designated for long-term support as *longterm* with bug fix releases for two or more years.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] Some projects have attempted to reduce the size of the Linux kernel.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p01] In 2014, Josh Triplett started the -tiny source tree for a reduced size version.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] Even though seemingly contradictory, the Linux kernel is both monolithic and modular.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] The kernel is classified as a monolithic kernel architecturally since the entire OS runs in kernel space.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] The design is modular since it can be assembled from modules that in some cases are loaded and unloaded at runtime.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] It supports features once only available in closed source kernels of non-free operating systems.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] The rest of the article makes use of the UNIX and Unix-like operating systems convention of the manual pages.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] The number that follows the name of a command, interface, or other feature specifies the section (i.e. the type of the OS' component or feature) it belongs to.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] For example execve(2) refers to a system call, and exec(3) refers to a userspace library wrapper.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] The following is an overview of architectural design and of noteworthy features.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] Most device drivers and kernel extensions run in kernel space (ring 0 in many CPU architectures), with full access to the hardware.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] Some exceptions run in user space; notable examples are filesystems based on FUSE/CUSE, and parts of UIO.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] Furthermore, the X Window System and Wayland, the windowing system and display server protocols that most people use with Linux, do not run within the kernel.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] Differently, the actual interfacing with GPUs of graphics cards is an in-kernel subsystem called Direct Rendering Manager (DRM).
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] Unlike standard monolithic kernels, device drivers are easily configured as modules, and loaded or unloaded while the system is running and can also be pre-empted under certain conditions in order to handle hardware interrupts correctly and to better support symmetric multiprocessing.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] By choice, Linux has no stable device driver application binary interface.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] Linux typically makes use of memory protection and virtual memory and can also handle non-uniform memory access, the project has absorbed μClinux, which also makes it possible to run Linux on microcontrollers without virtual memory.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] The hardware is represented in the file hierarchy.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] User applications interact with device drivers via entries in the /dev or /sys directories.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] Process information is mapped into the /proc directory.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] Linux started as a clone of UNIX, and aims toward POSIX and Single UNIX Specification compliance.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] The kernel provides system calls and other interfaces that are Linux-specific.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] In order to be included in the official kernel, the code must comply with a set of licensing rules.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] The Linux application binary interface (ABI) between the kernel and the user space has four degrees of stability (stable, testing, obsolete, removed); The system calls are expected to never change in order to preserve compatibility for userspace programs that rely on them.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] Loadable kernel modules (LKMs), by design, cannot rely on a stable ABI.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] Therefore, they must always be recompiled whenever a new kernel executable is installed in a system, otherwise they will not be loaded.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] In-tree drivers that are configured to become an integral part of the kernel executable (vmlinux) are statically linked by the build process.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] There is no guarantee of stability of source-level in-kernel API and, because of this, device driver code, as well as the code of any other kernel subsystem, must be kept updated with kernel evolution.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] Any developer who makes an API change is required to fix any code that breaks as the result of their change.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] The set of the Linux kernel API that regards the interfaces exposed to user applications is fundamentally composed of UNIX and Linux-specific system calls.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] A system call is an entry point into the Linux kernel.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] For example, among the Linux-specific ones there is the family of the clone(2) system calls.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] Most extensions must be enabled by defining the `_GNU_SOURCE` macro in a header file or when the user-land code is being compiled.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] System calls can only be invoked via assembly instructions that enable the transition from unprivileged user space to privileged kernel space in ring 0.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] For this reason, the C standard library (libC) acts as a wrapper to most Linux system calls, by exposing C functions that, if needed, transparently enter the kernel, which will execute on behalf of the calling process.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] For system calls not exposed by libC, such as the fast userspace mutex, the library provides a function called syscall(2), which can be used to explicitly invoke them.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] Pseudo filesystems (e.g., the sysfs and procfs filesystems) and special files (e.g., `/dev/random`, `/dev/sda`, `/dev/tty`, and many others) constitute another layer of interface to kernel data structures representing hardware or logical (software) devices.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] This issue is mainly due to distribution-specific configurations and a set of patches applied to the code of the Linux kernel, differences in system libraries, services (daemons), filesystem hierarchies, and environment variables.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] The main standard concerning application and binary compatibility of Linux distributions is the Linux Standard Base (LSB).
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] The LSB goes beyond what concerns the Linux kernel, because it also defines the desktop specifications, the X libraries and Qt that have little to do with it.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] The LSB version 5 is built upon several standards and drafts (POSIX, SUS, X/Open, File System Hierarchy (FHS), and others).
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] The standard ABI for how x86_64 user programs invoke system calls is to load the syscall number into the *rax* register, and the other parameters into *rdi*, *rsi*, *rdx*, *r10*, *r8*, and *r9*, and finally to put the *syscall* assembly instruction in the code.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] There are several internal kernel APIs between kernel subsystems.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] The Linux developers chose not to maintain a stable in-kernel ABI.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] Modules compiled for a specific version of the kernel cannot be loaded into another version without being recompiled.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] Linux, as other kernels, has the ability to manage processes including creating, suspending, resuming and terminating.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] Unlike other operating systems, the Linux kernel implements processes as a group of threads called tasks.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] If two tasks share the same TGID, then they are called in the kernel terminology a task group.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] Each task is represented by a *task_struct* data structure.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] A new process can be created by calling clone family of system calls or fork system call.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] Processes can be suspended and resumed by the kernel by sending signals like SIGSTOP and SIGCONT.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] A process can terminate itself by calling exit system call, or terminated by another process by sending signals like SIGKILL, SIGABRT or SIGINT.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] If the executable is dynamically linked to shared libraries, a dynamic linker is used to find and load the needed objects, prepare the program to run and then run it.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] The Native POSIX Thread Library (NPTL) provides the POSIX standard thread interface (*pthreads*) to userspace.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] The kernel isn't aware of processes nor threads but it is aware of *tasks*, thus threads are implemented in userspace.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] Threads in Linux are implemented as *tasks* sharing resources, while if they aren't sharing called to be independent processes.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] The kernel provides the futex(7) (fast user-space mutex) mechanisms for user-space locking and synchronization.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] The majority of the operations are performed in userspace but it may be necessary to communicate with the kernel using the futex(2) system call.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] As opposed to userspace threads described above, *kernel threads* run in kernel space.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] They are threads created by the kernel itself for specialized tasks; they are privileged like the kernel and aren't bound to any process or application.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] The Linux process scheduler is modular, in the sense that it enables different scheduling classes and policies.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] Scheduler classes are pluggable scheduler algorithms that can be registered with the base scheduler code.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] Each class schedules different types of processes.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] The core code of the scheduler iterates over each class in order of priority and chooses the highest priority scheduler that has a schedulable entity of type struct sched_entity ready to run.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] Entities may be threads, group of threads, and even all the processes of a specific user.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] Linux provides both user preemption as well as (selectable, up to) full kernel preemption.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] Preemption reduces latency, increases responsiveness, and makes Linux more suitable for desktop and real-time applications.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] This comes at a cost of throughput, as work being interrupted worsens cache behavior.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] For normal tasks, by default, the kernel uses the Completely Fair Scheduler (CFS) class, introduced in version 2.6.23.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] The scheduler is defined as a macro in a C header as `SCHED_NORMAL`.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] In other POSIX kernels, a similar policy known as `SCHED_OTHER` allocates CPU timeslices (i.e, it assigns absolute slices of the processor time depending on either predetermined or dynamically computed priority of each process).
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] With user preemption, the kernel scheduler can replace the current process with the execution of a context switch to a different one that therefore acquires the computing resources for running (CPU, memory, and more).
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] With kernel preemption, the kernel can preempt itself when an interrupt handler returns, when kernel tasks block, and whenever a subsystem explicitly calls the schedule() function.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] The kernel also contains two POSIX-compliant real-time scheduling classes named `SCHED_FIFO` (realtime first-in-first-out) and `SCHED_RR` (realtime round-robin), both of which take precedence over the default class.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] An additional scheduling policy known as `SCHED_DEADLINE`, implementing the earliest deadline first algorithm (EDF), was added in kernel version 3.14, released on 30 March 2014.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] `SCHED_DEADLINE` takes precedence over all the other scheduling classes.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] In 2023, Peter Zijlstra proposed replacing CFS with an earliest eligible virtual deadline first scheduling (EEVDF) scheduler, to prevent the need for CFS "latency nice" patches.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] The EEVDF scheduler replaced CFS in version 6.6 of the Linux kernel.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] The kernel has different causes of concurrency (e.g., interrupts, bottom halves, preemption of kernel and users tasks, symmetrical multiprocessing).
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] They consist of atomic types (which can only be manipulated by a set of specific operators), spinlocks, semaphores, mutexes, and lockless algorithms (e.g., RCUs).
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] Most lock-less algorithms are built on top of memory barriers for the purpose of enforcing memory ordering and prevent undesired side effects due to compiler optimization.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] PREEMPT_RT code included in mainline Linux provide *RT-mutexes*, a special kind of Mutex that do not disable preemption and have support for priority inheritance.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] Almost all locks are changed into sleeping locks when using configuration for realtime operation.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] Priority inheritance avoids priority inversion by granting a low-priority task that holds a contended lock the priority of a higher-priority waiter until that lock is released.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] Linux includes a kernel lock validator called *Lockdep*.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] Although the management of interrupts could be seen as a single job, it is divided into two.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] This split in two is due to the different time constraints and to the synchronization needs of the tasks whose the management is composed of.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] The first part is made up of an asynchronous interrupt service routine (ISR) that in Linux is known as the *top half*, while the second part is carried out by one of three types of the so-called *bottom halves* (*softirq*, *tasklets,* and *work queues*).
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] Linux interrupt service routines can be nested.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] A new IRQ can trap into a high priority ISR that preempts any other lower priority ISR.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] The Linux kernel manages both physical and virtual memory.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] It divides physical memory into zones, each of which has a specific purpose.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] Those zones are the most common, but others exist.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] Linux implements virtual memory with 4 or 5-level page tables.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] The kernel is not pageable (meaning it is always resident in physical memory and cannot be swapped to the disk) and there is no memory protection (no SIGSEGV signals, unlike in user space), therefore memory violations lead to instability and system crashes.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] User memory is pageable by default, although paging for specific memory areas can be disabled with the `mlock()` system call family.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] Page frame information is maintained in apposite data structures (of type `struct page`) that are populated immediately after boot and kept until shutdown, regardless of whether they are associated with virtual pages.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] The physical address space is divided into different zones, according to architectural constraints and intended use.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] NUMA systems with multiple memory banks are also supported.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] Small chunks of memory can be dynamically allocated in kernel space via the family of `kmalloc()` APIs and freed with the appropriate variant of `kfree()`.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] `vmalloc()` and `kvfree()` are used for large virtually contiguous chunks.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] `alloc_pages()` allocates the desired number of entire pages.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] The kernel used to include the SLAB, SLUB and SLOB allocators as configurable alternatives.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] The SLOB allocator was removed in Linux 6.4 and the SLAB allocator was removed in Linux 6.8.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] The sole remaining allocator is SLUB, which aims for simplicity and efficiency, is PREEMPT_RT compatible and was introduced in Linux 2.6.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] Since Linux supports numerous filesystems with different features and functionality, it is necessary to implement a generic filesystem that is independent from underlying filesystems.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] The virtual file system interfaces with other Linux subsystems, userspace, or APIs and abstracts away the different implementations of underlying filesystems.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] VFS implements system calls like `create`, `open`, `read`, `write` and `close`.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] VFS implements a generic superblock and inode block that is independent from the one that the underlying filesystem has.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] In this subsystem directories and files are represented by a `struct file` data structure.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] When userspace requests access to a file it is returned a file descriptor (non negative integer value) but in kernel space it is a `struct file` structure.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] This structure stores all the information the kernel knows about a file or directory.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] sysfs and procfs are virtual filesystems that expose hardware information and userspace programs' runtime information.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] These filesystems aren't present on disk and instead the kernel implements them as a callback or routine that gets called when they are accessed by userspace.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] While not originally designed to be portable, Linux is now one of the most widely ported operating system kernels, running on a diverse range of systems from the ARM architecture to IBM z/Architecture mainframe computers.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] The first port was performed on the Motorola 68000 platform.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] The modifications to the kernel were so fundamental that Torvalds viewed the Motorola version as a fork and a "Linux-like operating system".
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] That moved Torvalds to lead a major restructure of the code to facilitate porting to more computing architectures.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] The first Linux that, in a single source tree, had code for more than i386 alone, supported the DEC Alpha AXP 64-bit platform.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] Linux is used as the primary operating system on IBM’s Summit supercomputer.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] In October 2019, all systems on the TOP500 list of the world’s fastest supercomputers ran operating systems based on the Linux kernel, whereas the first Linux-based supercomputer appeared on the list in 1998.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] Linux has also been ported to various handheld devices such as iPhone 3G and iPod.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] In 2007, the LKDDb project has been started to build a comprehensive database of hardware and protocols known by Linux kernels.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] The database is built automatically by static analysis of the kernel sources.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] Later in 2014, the Linux Hardware project was launched to automatically collect a database of all tested hardware configurations with the help of users of various Linux distributions.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] Kernel updates can be applied without rebooting by using live patching technologies such as Ksplice, kpatch and kGraft.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] Initial support for live kernel patching was merged into the Linux kernel mainline in version 4.0, released on 12 April 2015.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] The feature, known as *livepatch*, uses the kernel's ftrace functionality and provides a common infrastructure for hot patches supplied through kernel modules, together with interfaces for userspace management tools.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] In its initial Linux 4.0 implementation, livepatch support was limited to the x86 architecture and provided basic infrastructure rather than a complete live-patching consistency model.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] Kernel bugs present potential security issues.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] For example, they may allow for privilege escalation or create denial-of-service attack vectors.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] Over the years, numerous bugs affecting system security were found and fixed.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] New features are frequently implemented to improve the kernel's security.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] Capabilities(7) have already been introduced in the section about the processes and threads.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] Android makes use of them and systemd gives administrators detailed control over the capabilities of processes.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] Linux offers a wealth of mechanisms to reduce kernel attack surface and improve security that are collectively known as the Linux Security Modules (LSM).
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] They comprise the Security-Enhanced Linux (SELinux) module, whose code has been originally developed and then released to the public by the NSA, and AppArmor among others.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] SELinux is now actively developed and maintained on GitHub.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] SELinux and AppArmor provide support to access control security policies, including mandatory access control (MAC), though they profoundly differ in complexity and scope.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] Another security feature is the Seccomp BPF (SECure COMPuting with Berkeley Packet Filters), which works by filtering parameters and reducing the set of system calls available to user-land applications.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] Linux distributions typically release security updates to fix vulnerabilities in the Linux kernel.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] Many offer long-term support releases that receive security updates for a certain Linux kernel version for an extended period of time.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] In 2024, researchers disclosed that the Linux kernel contained a serious vulnerability, CVE-2024-50264, located in the AF_VSOCK subsystem.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] This bug is a use-after-free flaw, a class of memory corruption issue that occurs when a program continues to use memory after it has been freed.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] Such flaws are particularly dangerous in the kernel, as they can allow attackers to escalate privileges.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] Initially, Torvalds released Linux under a license that forbade any commercial use.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] This was changed in version 0.12 by a switch to the GNU General Public License version 2 (GPLv2).
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] This license allows distribution and sale of possibly modified and unmodified versions of Linux but requires that all those copies be released under the same license and be accompanied by - or that, on request, free access is given to - the complete corresponding source code.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] Torvalds has described licensing Linux under the GPLv2 as the "best thing I ever did".
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] The Linux kernel is licensed explicitly under GNU General Public License version 2 only (GPL-2.0-only) with an explicit syscall exception (Linux-syscall-note), without offering the licensee the option to choose any later version, which is a common GPL extension.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] Contributed code must be available under GPL-compatible license.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] There was considerable debate about how easily the license could be changed to use later GPL versions (including version 3), and whether this change is even desirable.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] Torvalds himself specifically indicated upon the release of version 2.4.0 that his own code is released only under version 2.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] The terms of the GPL state that if no version is specified, then any version may be used, and Alan Cox pointed out that very few other Linux contributors had specified a particular version of the GPL.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] In September 2006, a survey of 29 key kernel programmers indicated that 28 preferred GPLv2 to the then-current GPLv3 draft.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] They referred to clauses regarding DRM/tivoization, patents, "additional restrictions" and warned a Balkanisation of the "Open Source Universe" by the GPLv3.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] Torvalds, who decided not to adopt the GPLv3 for the Linux kernel, reiterated his criticism even years later.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] It is debated whether some loadable kernel modules (LKMs) are to be considered derivative works under copyright law, and thereby whether or not they fall under the terms of the GPL.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] In accordance with the license rules, LKMs using only a public subset of the kernel interfaces are non-derived works, thus Linux gives system administrators the mechanisms to load out-of-tree binary objects into the kernel address space.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] There are some out-of-tree loadable modules that make legitimate use of the *dma_buf* kernel feature.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] GPL compliant code can certainly use it.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] A different possible use case would be Nvidia Optimus that pairs a fast GPU with an Intel integrated GPU, where the Nvidia GPU writes into the Intel framebuffer when it is active.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] But, Nvidia cannot use this infrastructure because it necessitates bypassing a rule that can only be used by LKMs that are also GPL.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] Alan Cox replied on LKML, rejecting a request from one of Nvidia's engineers to remove this technical enforcement from the API.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] Torvalds clearly stated on the LKML that "[I] claim that binary-only kernel modules ARE derivative "by default"'".
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] On the other hand, Torvalds has also said that "[one] gray area in particular is something like a driver that was originally written for another operating system (i.e., clearly not a derived work of Linux in origin).
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] THAT is a gray area, and _that_ is the area where I personally believe that some modules may be considered to not be derived works simply because they weren't designed for Linux and don't depend on any special Linux behaviour".
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] Proprietary graphics drivers, in particular, are heavily discussed.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] Whenever proprietary modules are loaded into Linux, the kernel marks itself as being "tainted", and therefore bug reports from tainted kernels will often be ignored by developers.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] The official kernel, that is, Torvalds's git branch at the kernel.org repository, contains binary blobs released under the terms of the GNU GPLv2 license.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] Linux can also load binary blobs, proprietary firmware, drivers, or other executable modules from the filesystem, and link them into kernel space.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] Linux is a registered trademark of Linus Torvalds in the United States, the European Union, and some other countries.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] A legal battle over the trademark began in 1996, when William Della Croce, a lawyer who was never involved in the development of Linux, started requesting licensing fees for the use of the word *Linux*.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] After it was proven that the word was in common use long before Della Croce's claimed first use, the trademark was awarded to Torvalds.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] In October 2024, during the Russian invasion of Ukraine, kernel developer Greg Kroah-Hartman removed some kernel developers whose email addresses suggested a connection to Russia from their roles as maintainers.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] Linus Torvalds responded that he did not support Russian aggression and would not revert the patch, insinuating that opponents of the patch were Russian trolls.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/linux-kernel-p02] James Bottomley, a kernel developer, issued an apology for the handling of the situation and clarified that the action was a consequence of U.S. sanctions against Russia.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/preempt-rt] The PREEMPT_RT patchset has been in development since 2005 as an effort to make the Linux kernel capable of real-time computing by reducing unbounded latencies in kernel paths.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/preempt-rt] Early real-time enhancements were proposed by Ingo Molnár, Thomas Gleixner, and others.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/preempt-rt] The PREEMPT_RT patch series introduced features such as threaded interrupts, priority-inherited mutexes, and other mechanisms required for deterministic kernel behavior.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/preempt-rt] For many years PREEMPT_RT was maintained as an out-of-tree patch set applied to stable kernel releases.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/preempt-rt] To support the funding of the ongoing development OSADL, a German software organization with members from PREEMPT_RTs user but also its creators like Gleixners Linutronix, has a working group.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/preempt-rt] While parts of the PREEMPT_RT work were incrementally merged, the majority of the patch set remained external to mainline Linux for decades.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/preempt-rt] In 2015, the Linux Foundation established the Real-Time Linux (RTL) Collaborative Project to coordinate efforts toward upstreaming PREEMPT_RT and to provide sustained development resources.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/preempt-rt] The project brought together long term industry members and maintainers to focus on refactoring kernel subsystems and pushing critical real-time code into the mainline.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/preempt-rt] In 2021, the preemption core locking code was merged.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/preempt-rt] At the September 2024 European Open Source Summit, Linus Torvalds announced that PREEMPT_RT had been accepted into the mainline Linux kernel after a protracted development hurdle involving the `printk` kernel logging facility.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/preempt-rt] PREEMPT-RT is actively used at the moment by distributors and vendors to enhance their own distributions.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/preempt-rt] MontaVista Software has been releasing a real-time Linux distribution containing the PREEMPT_RT patchset since the early 2000.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/preempt-rt] Montavista's current main embedded Linux product, CGX, contains real-time preemption as a standard feature.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/preempt-rt] Since February 2023, Canonical sold real-time versions of Ubuntu Pro., even though no notable contributions were made to the development by them.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/preemption-computing] In computing, **preemption** is the act performed by an external scheduler — without assistance or cooperation from the task — of temporarily interrupting an executing task, with the intention of resuming it at a later time.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/preemption-computing] This preemptive scheduler usually runs in the most privileged protection ring, meaning that interruption and then resumption are considered highly secure actions.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/preemption-computing] Such changes to the currently executing task of a processor are known as context switching.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/preemption-computing] In any given system design, some operations performed by the system may not be preemptable.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/preemption-computing] This usually applies to kernel functions and service interrupts which, if not permitted to run to completion, would tend to produce race conditions resulting in deadlock.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/preemption-computing] Barring the scheduler from preempting tasks while they are processing kernel functions simplifies the kernel design at the expense of system responsiveness.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/preemption-computing] The distinction between user mode and kernel mode, which determines privilege level within the system, may also be used to distinguish whether a task is currently preemptable.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/preemption-computing] Most modern operating systems have **preemptive kernels**, which are designed to permit tasks to be preempted even when in kernel mode.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/preemption-computing] Examples of such operating systems are Solaris 2.0/SunOS 5.0, Windows NT, Linux kernel (2.5.4 and newer), AIX and some BSD systems (NetBSD, since version 5).
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/preemption-computing] The term **preemptive multitasking** is used to distinguish a multitasking operating system, which permits preemption of tasks, from a cooperative multitasking system wherein processes or tasks must be explicitly programmed to yield when they do not need system resources.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/preemption-computing] In simple terms: Preemptive multitasking involves the use of an interrupt mechanism which suspends the currently executing process and invokes a scheduler to determine which process should execute next.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/preemption-computing] Therefore, all processes will get some amount of CPU time at any given time.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/preemption-computing] In preemptive multitasking, the operating system kernel can also initiate a context switch to satisfy the scheduling policy's priority constraint, thus preempting the active task.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/preemption-computing] In general, preemption means "prior seizure of".
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/preemption-computing] When the high-priority task at that instance seizes the currently running task, it is known as preemptive scheduling.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/preemption-computing] The term "preemptive multitasking" is sometimes mistakenly used when the intended meaning is more specific, referring instead to the class of scheduling policies known as *time-shared scheduling*, or *time-sharing*.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/preemption-computing] Preemptive multitasking allows the computer system to more reliably guarantee each process a regular "slice" of operating time.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/preemption-computing] It also allows the system to rapidly deal with important external events like incoming data, which might require the immediate attention of one or another process.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/preemption-computing] At any specific time, processes can be grouped into two categories: those that are waiting for input or output (called "I/O bound"), and those that are fully utilizing the CPU ("CPU bound").
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/preemption-computing] In early systems, processes would often "poll" or "busy-wait" while waiting for requested input (such as disk, keyboard or network input).
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/preemption-computing] During this time, the process was not performing useful work, but still maintained complete control of the CPU.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/preemption-computing] With the advent of interrupts and preemptive multitasking, these I/O bound processes could be "blocked", or put on hold, pending the arrival of the necessary data, allowing other processes to utilize the CPU.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/preemption-computing] As the arrival of the requested data would generate an interrupt, blocked processes could be guaranteed a timely return to execution.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/preemption-computing] Although multitasking techniques were originally developed to allow multiple users to share a single machine, it became apparent that multitasking was useful regardless of the number of users.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/preemption-computing] Many operating systems, from mainframes down to single-user personal computers and no-user control systems (like those in robotic spacecraft), have recognized the usefulness of multitasking support for a variety of reasons.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/preemption-computing] Multitasking makes it possible for a single user to run multiple applications at the same time, or to run "background" processes while retaining control of the computer.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/preemption-computing] The period of time for which a process is allowed to run in a preemptive multitasking system is generally called the *time slice* or *quantum*.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/preemption-computing] The scheduler is run once every time slice to choose the next process to run.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/preemption-computing] The length of each time slice can be critical to balancing system performance vs process responsiveness - if the time slice is too short then the scheduler itself will consume too much processing time, but if the time slice is too long, processes will take longer to respond to input.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/preemption-computing] An interrupt is scheduled to allow the operating system kernel to switch between processes when their time slices expire, effectively allowing the processor's time to be shared among a number of tasks, giving the illusion that it is dealing with these tasks in parallel (simultaneously).
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/preemption-computing] The operating system which controls such a design is called a multi-tasking system.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/preemption-computing] Today, nearly all operating systems support preemptive multitasking, including the current versions of Windows, Linux (including Android), and Darwin (including macOS and iOS).
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/preemption-computing] Sinclair QDOS and AmigaOS on the Amiga were also microcomputer operating systems offering preemptive multitasking as a core feature.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/preemption-computing] These both ran on Motorola 68000-family microprocessors without memory management.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/preemption-computing] Amiga OS used dynamic loading of relocatable code blocks ("hunks" in Amiga jargon) to multitask preemptively all processes in the same flat address space.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/preemption-computing] Early operating systems for IBM PC compatibles such as MS-DOS and PC DOS, did not support multitasking at all, however alternative operating systems such as MP/M-86 (1981) and Concurrent CP/M-86 did support preemptive multitasking.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/preemption-computing] Other Unix-like systems including MINIX and Coherent provided preemptive multitasking on 1980s-era personal computers.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/preemption-computing] Later MS-DOS compatible systems natively supporting preemptive multitasking/multithreading include Concurrent DOS, Multiuser DOS, Novell DOS (later called Caldera OpenDOS and DR-DOS 7.02 and higher).
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/preemption-computing] Since Concurrent DOS 386, they could also run multiple DOS programs concurrently in virtual DOS machines.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/preemption-computing] The earliest version of Windows to support a limited form of preemptive multitasking was Windows/386 2.0, which used the Intel 80386's Virtual 8086 mode to run DOS applications in virtual 8086 machines, commonly known as "DOS boxes", which could be preempted.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/preemption-computing] In Windows 95, 98 and Me, 32-bit applications were made preemptive by running each one in a separate address space, but 16-bit applications remained cooperative for backward compatibility.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/preemption-computing] In Windows 3.1x (protected mode), the kernel and virtual device drivers ran preemptively, but all 16-bit applications were non-preemptive and shared the same address space.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/preemption-computing] Preemptive multitasking has always been supported by Windows NT (all versions), OS/2 (native applications), Unix and Unix-like systems (such as Linux, BSD and macOS), VMS, OS/360, and many other operating systems designed for use in the academic and medium-to-large business markets.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/preemption-computing] Early versions of the classic Mac OS did not support multitasking at all, with cooperative multitasking becoming available via MultiFinder in System Software 5 and then standard in System 7.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/real-time-computing] The term "real-time" is also used in simulation to mean that the simulation's clock runs at the same speed as a real clock.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/real-time-computing] Real-time responses are often understood to be in the order of milliseconds, and sometimes microseconds.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/real-time-computing] A system not specified as operating in real time cannot usually *guarantee* a response within any timeframe, although *typical* or *expected* response times may be given.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/real-time-computing] Real-time processing *fails* if not completed within a specified deadline relative to an event; deadlines must always be met, regardless of system load.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/real-time-computing] A real-time system has been described as one which "controls an environment by receiving data, processing them, and returning the results sufficiently quickly to affect the environment at that time".
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/real-time-computing] The term "real-time" is used in process control and enterprise systems to mean "without significant delay".
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/real-time-computing] Real-time software may use one or more of the following: synchronous programming languages, real-time operating systems (RTOSes), and real-time networks.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/real-time-computing] Each of these provides essential frameworks on which to build a real-time software application.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/real-time-computing] Systems used for many safety-critical applications must be real-time, such as for control of fly-by-wire aircraft, or anti-lock brakes, both of which demand immediate and accurate mechanical response.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/real-time-computing] The term *real-time* derives from its use in early simulation, where a real-world process is simulated at a rate which matched that of the real process (now called real-time simulation to avoid ambiguity).
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/real-time-computing] Analog computers, most often, were capable of simulating at a much faster pace than real-time, a situation that could be just as dangerous as a slow simulation if it were not also recognized and accounted for.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/real-time-computing] Minicomputers, particularly from the 1970s onwards, when built into dedicated embedded systems such as DOG (digital on-screen graphic) scanners, increased the need for low-latency priority-driven responses to important interactions with incoming data.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/real-time-computing] Operating systems such as Data General's RDOS (Real-Time Disk Operating System) and RTOS with background and foreground scheduling as well as Digital Equipment Corporation's RT-11 date from this era.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/real-time-computing] Background-foreground scheduling allowed low-priority tasks CPU time when no foreground task needed to execute, and gave absolute priority within the foreground to threads/tasks with the highest priority.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/real-time-computing] Real-time operating systems would also be used for time-sharing multiuser duties.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/real-time-computing] For example, Data General Business Basic could run in the foreground or background of RDOS and would introduce additional elements to the scheduling algorithm to make it more appropriate for people interacting via dumb terminals.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/real-time-computing] Early personal computers were sometimes used for real-time computing.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/real-time-computing] The possibility of deactivating other interrupts allowed for hard-coded loops with defined timing, and the low interrupt latency allowed the implementation of a real-time operating system, giving the user interface and the disk drives lower priority than the real-time thread.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/real-time-computing] However, several coding libraries exist that offer real-time capabilities in a high-level language on a variety of operating systems, for example, Real-time Java.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/real-time-computing] Later microprocessors such as the Motorola 68000 and subsequent family members (68010, 68020, ColdFire, etc.) also became popular with manufacturers of industrial control systems.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/real-time-computing] This application area is one where real-time control offers genuine advantages in terms of process performance and safety.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/real-time-computing] A system is said to be *real-time* if the total correctness of an operation depends not only upon its logical correctness, but also upon the time in which it is performed.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/real-time-computing] Thus, the goal of a *hard real-time system* is to ensure that all deadlines are met, but for *soft real-time systems* the goal becomes meeting a certain subset of deadlines in order to optimize some application-specific criteria.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/real-time-computing] The particular criteria optimized depend on the application, but some typical examples include maximizing the number of deadlines met, minimizing the lateness of tasks and maximizing the number of high-priority tasks meeting their deadlines.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/real-time-computing] In the context of multitasking systems the scheduling policy is normally priority driven (pre-emptive schedulers).
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/real-time-computing] In some situations, these can guarantee hard real-time performance (for instance, if the set of tasks and their priorities is known in advance).
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/real-time-computing] There are other hard real-time schedulers such as rate-monotonic, which is not common in general-purpose systems, as it requires additional information in order to schedule a task: namely, a bound or worst-case estimate for how long the task must execute.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/real-time-computing] Specific algorithms for scheduling such hard real-time tasks exist, like earliest deadline first, which, ignoring the overhead of context switching, is sufficient for system loads of less than 100%.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/real-time-computing] New overlay scheduling systems, such as an adaptive partition scheduler assist in managing large systems with a mixture of hard real-time and non real-time applications.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/real-time-computing] In a real-time digital signal processing (DSP) process, the analyzed (input) and generated (output) samples can be processed (or generated) continuously in the time it takes to input and output the same set of samples *independent* of the processing delay.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/real-time-computing] It means that the processing delay must be bounded even if the processing continues for an unlimited time.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/real-time-computing] The mean processing time per sample, including overhead, is no greater than the sampling period, which is the reciprocal of the sampling rate.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/real-time-computing] This is the criterion whether the samples are grouped together in large segments and processed as blocks or are processed individually and whether there are long, short, or non-existent input and output buffers.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/real-time-computing] Consider an audio DSP example; if a process requires 2.01 seconds to analyze, synthesize, or process 2.00 seconds of sound, it is not real-time.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/real-time-computing] However, if it takes 1.99 seconds, it is or can be made into a real-time DSP process.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/real-time-computing] A common life analogy is standing in a line or queue waiting for the checkout in a grocery store.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/real-time-computing] If the line asymptotically grows longer and longer without bound, the checkout process is not real-time.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/real-time-computing] If the length of the line is bounded, customers are being "processed" and output as rapidly, on average, as they are being inputted, then that process *is* real-time.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/real-time-computing] The grocer might go out of business or must at least lose business if they cannot make their checkout process real-time; thus, it is fundamentally important that this process is real-time.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/real-time-computing] A signal processing algorithm that cannot keep up with the flow of input data, with output falling further and further behind the input, is not real-time.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/real-time-computing] If the delay of the output (relative to the input) is bounded regarding a process that operates over an unlimited time, then that signal processing algorithm is real-time, even if the throughput delay may be very long.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/real-time-computing] Real-time signal processing is necessary, but not sufficient in and of itself, for live signal processing such as what is required in live event support.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/real-time-computing] Live audio digital signal processing requires both real-time operation and a sufficient limit to throughput delay so as to be tolerable to performers using stage monitors or in-ear monitors and not noticeable as lip sync error by the audience also directly watching the performers.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/real-time-computing] Tolerable limits to latency for live, real-time processing is a subject of investigation and debate, but is estimated to be between 6 and 20 milliseconds.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/real-time-computing] Real-time bidirectional telecommunications delays of less than 300 ms ("round trip" or twice the unidirectional delay) are considered "acceptable" to avoid undesired "talk-over" in conversation.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/real-time-computing] Real-time computing is sometimes misunderstood to be high-performance computing, but this is not an accurate classification.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/real-time-computing] For example, a massive supercomputer executing a scientific simulation may offer impressive performance, yet it is not executing a real-time computation.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/real-time-computing] Conversely, once the hardware and software for an anti-lock braking system have been designed to meet its required deadlines, no further performance gains are obligatory or even useful.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/real-time-computing] Furthermore, if a network server is highly loaded with network traffic, its response time may be slower, but will (in most cases) still succeed before it times out (hits its deadline).
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/real-time-computing] Hence, such a network server would not be considered a real-time system: temporal failures (delays, time-outs, etc.) are typically small and compartmentalized (limited in effect), but are not catastrophic failures.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/real-time-computing] In a real-time system, such as the FTSE 100 Index, a slowdown beyond limits would often be considered catastrophic in its application context.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/real-time-computing] The most important requirement of a real-time system is consistent output, not high throughput.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/real-time-computing] Some kinds of software, such as many chess-playing programs, can fall into either category.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/real-time-computing] For instance, a chess program designed to play in a tournament with a clock will need to decide on a move before a certain deadline or lose the game, and is therefore a real-time computation, but a chess program that is allowed to run indefinitely before moving is not.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/real-time-computing] In both of these cases, however, high performance is desirable: the more work a tournament chess program can do in the allotted time, the better its moves will be, and the faster an unconstrained chess program runs, the sooner it will be able to move.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/real-time-computing] High performance is indicative of the amount of processing that is performed in a given amount of time, whereas real-time is the ability to get done with the processing to yield a useful output in the available time.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/real-time-computing] For example, a near-real-time display depicts an event or situation as it existed at the current time minus the processing time, as nearly the time of the live event.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/real-time-computing] The distinction between the terms "near real time" and "real time" is somewhat nebulous and must be defined for the situation at hand.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/real-time-computing] The term implies that there are no significant delays.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/real-time-computing] In many cases, processing described as "real-time" would be more accurately described as "near real-time".
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/real-time-computing] Near real-time also refers to delayed real-time transmission of voice and video.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/real-time-computing] It allows playing video images, in approximately real-time, without having to wait for an entire large video file to download.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/real-time-computing] Incompatible databases can export/import to common flat files that the other database can import/export on a scheduled basis so they can sync/share common data in "near real-time" with each other.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/real-time-computing] Several methods exist to aid the design of real-time systems, an example of which is MASCOT, an old but very successful method that represents the concurrent structure of the system.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/real-time-computing] Other examples are HOOD, Real-Time UML, AADL, the Ravenscar profile, and Real-time Java.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] In computing, **scheduling** is the action of assigning resources to perform tasks.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] The resources may be processors, network links or expansion cards.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] The tasks may be threads, processes or data flows.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] The scheduling activity is carried out by a mechanism called a **scheduler**.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] Schedulers are often designed so as to keep all computer resources busy (as in load balancing), allow multiple users to share system resources effectively, or to achieve a target quality-of-service.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] Scheduling is fundamental to computation itself, and an intrinsic part of the execution model of a computer system; the concept of scheduling makes it possible to have computer multitasking with a single central processing unit (CPU).
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] In practice, these goals often conflict (e.g. throughput versus latency), thus a scheduler will implement a suitable compromise.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] Preference is measured by any one of the concerns mentioned above, depending upon the user's needs and objectives.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] In real-time environments, such as embedded systems for automatic control in industry (for example robotics), the scheduler also must ensure that processes can meet deadlines; this is crucial for keeping the system stable.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] Scheduled tasks can also be distributed to remote devices across a network and managed through an administrative back end.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] The scheduler is an operating system module that selects the next jobs to be admitted into the system and the next process to run.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] Operating systems may feature up to three distinct scheduler types: a *long-term scheduler* (also known as an admission scheduler or high-level scheduler), a *mid-term or medium-term scheduler*, and a *short-term scheduler*.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] The names suggest the relative frequency with which their functions are performed.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] The process scheduler is a part of the operating system that decides which process runs at a certain point in time.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] It usually has the ability to pause a running process, move it to the back of the running queue and start a new process; such a scheduler is known as a *preemptive scheduler*.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] If the scheduler cannot pause a running process and start a new process, the scheduler is a *cooperative scheduler*.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] We distinguish between *long-term scheduling*, *medium-term scheduling*, and *short-term scheduling* based on how often decisions must be made.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] Thus, this scheduler dictates what processes are to run on a system, the degree of concurrency to be supported at any one time – whether many or few processes are to be executed concurrently, and how the split between I/O-intensive and CPU-intensive processes is to be handled.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] The long-term scheduler is responsible for controlling the degree of multiprogramming.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] In general, most processes can be described as either I/O-bound or CPU-bound.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] An I/O-bound process is one that spends more of its time doing I/O than it spends doing computations.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] A CPU-bound process, in contrast, generates I/O requests infrequently, using more of its time doing computations.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] It is important that a long-term scheduler selects a good process mix of I/O-bound and CPU-bound processes.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] If all processes are I/O-bound, the ready queue will almost always be empty, and the short-term scheduler will have little to do.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] On the other hand, if all processes are CPU-bound, the I/O waiting queue will almost always be empty, devices will go unused, and again the system will be unbalanced.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] The system with the best performance will thus have a combination of CPU-bound and I/O-bound processes.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] In modern operating systems, this is used to make sure that real-time processes get enough CPU time to finish their tasks.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] Long-term scheduling is also important in large-scale systems such as batch processing systems, computer clusters, supercomputers, and render farms.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] For example, in concurrent systems, coscheduling of interacting processes is often required to prevent them from blocking due to waiting on each other.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] In these cases, special-purpose job scheduler software is typically used to assist these functions, in addition to any underlying admission scheduling support in the operating system.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] Some operating systems only allow new tasks to be added if it is sure all real-time deadlines can still be met.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] The specific heuristic algorithm used by an operating system to accept or reject new tasks is the *admission control mechanism*.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] The *medium-term scheduler* temporarily removes processes from main memory and places them in secondary memory (such as a hard disk drive) or vice versa, which is commonly referred to as *swapping out* or *swapping in* (also incorrectly as *paging out* or *paging in*).
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] In many systems today (those that support mapping virtual address space to secondary storage other than the swap file), the medium-term scheduler may actually perform the role of the long-term scheduler, by treating binaries as *swapped-out processes* upon their execution.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] In this way, when a segment of the binary is required, it can be swapped in on demand, or *lazy loaded*, also called demand paging.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] The *short-term scheduler* (also known as the *CPU scheduler*) decides which of the ready, in-memory processes is to be executed (allocated a CPU) after a clock interrupt, an I/O interrupt, an operating system call or another form of signal.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] Thus, the short-term scheduler makes scheduling decisions much more frequently than the long-term or mid-term schedulers – A scheduling decision will, at a minimum, have to be made after every time slice, and these are very short.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] This scheduler can be preemptive, implying that it is capable of forcibly removing processes from a CPU when it decides to allocate that CPU to another process, or non-preemptive (also known as *voluntary* or *co-operative*), in which case the scheduler is unable to *force* processes off the CPU.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] Another component that is involved in the CPU-scheduling function is the dispatcher, which is the module that gives control of the CPU to the process selected by the short-term scheduler.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] It receives control in kernel mode as the result of an interrupt or system call.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] The dispatcher should be as fast as possible since it is invoked during every process switch.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] During the context switches, the processor is virtually idle for a fraction of time, thus unnecessary context switches should be avoided.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] The time it takes for the dispatcher to stop one process and start another is known as the *dispatch latency*.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] A **scheduling discipline** (also called **scheduling policy** or **scheduling algorithm**) is an algorithm used for distributing resources among parties that simultaneously and asynchronously request them.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] Scheduling disciplines are used in routers (to handle packet traffic) as well as in operating systems (to share CPU time among both threads and processes), disk drives (I/O scheduling), printers (print spooler), most embedded systems, etc.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] The main purposes of scheduling algorithms are to minimize resource starvation and to ensure fairness amongst the parties utilizing the resources.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] Scheduling deals with the problem of deciding which of the outstanding requests is to be allocated resources.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] There are many different scheduling algorithms.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] In this section, we introduce several of them.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] In packet-switched computer networks and other statistical multiplexing, the notion of a **scheduling algorithm** is used as an alternative to first-come first-served queuing of data packets.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] The simplest best-effort scheduling algorithms are round-robin, fair queuing (a max-min fair scheduling algorithm), proportional-fair scheduling and maximum throughput.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] If differentiated or guaranteed quality of service is offered, as opposed to best-effort communication, weighted fair queuing may be utilized.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] In advanced packet radio wireless networks such as HSDPA (High-Speed Downlink Packet Access) 3.5G cellular system, **channel-dependent scheduling** may be used to take advantage of channel state information.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] If the channel conditions are favourable, the throughput and system spectral efficiency may be increased.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] In even more advanced systems such as LTE, the scheduling is combined by channel-dependent packet-by-packet dynamic channel allocation, or by assigning OFDMA multi-carriers or other frequency-domain equalization components to the users that best can utilize them.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] Earliest deadline first (EDF) or *least time to go* is a dynamic scheduling algorithm used in real-time operating systems to place processes in a priority queue.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] Whenever a scheduling event occurs (a task finishes, a new task is released, etc.), the queue will be searched for the process closest to its deadline, which will be the next to be scheduled for execution.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] With this strategy the scheduler arranges processes with the least estimated processing time remaining to be next in the queue.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] This requires advanced knowledge or estimations about the time required for a process to complete.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] The operating system assigns a fixed-priority rank to every process, and the scheduler arranges the processes in the ready queue in order of their priority.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] Lower-priority processes get interrupted by incoming higher-priority processes.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] The scheduler assigns a fixed time unit per process, and cycles through them.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] If the process completes within that time slice, it gets terminated otherwise, it is rescheduled after giving a chance to all other processes.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] This is used for situations in which processes are easily divided into different groups.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] For example, a common division is made between foreground (interactive) processes and background (batch) processes.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] These two types of processes have different response-time requirements and so may have different scheduling needs.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] It is very useful for shared memory problems.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] A work-conserving scheduler is a scheduler that always tries to keep the scheduled resources busy if there are submitted jobs ready to be scheduled.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] In contrast, a non-work-conserving scheduler is a scheduler that, in some cases, may leave the scheduled resources idle despite the presence of jobs ready to be scheduled.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] A very common method in embedded systems is to schedule jobs manually.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] This can, for example, be done in a time-multiplexed fashion.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] Sometimes the kernel is divided in three or more parts: Manual scheduling, preemptive and interrupt level.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] Exact methods for scheduling jobs are often proprietary.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] When designing an operating system, a programmer must consider which scheduling algorithm will perform best for the use the system is going to see.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] There is no universal *best* scheduling algorithm, and many operating systems use extended or combinations of the scheduling algorithms above.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] For example, Windows NT/XP/Vista uses a multilevel feedback queue, a combination of fixed-priority preemptive scheduling, round-robin, and first-in, first-out algorithms.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] In this system, threads can dynamically increase or decrease in priority depending on if it has been serviced already or if it has been waiting extensively.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] Every priority level is represented by its own queue, with round-robin scheduling among the high-priority threads and FIFO among the lower-priority ones.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] In this sense, response time is short for most threads, and short but critical system threads get completed very quickly.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] Since threads can only use one time unit of the round-robin in the highest-priority queue, starvation can be a problem for longer high-priority threads.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] The algorithm used may be as simple as round-robin in which each process is given equal time (for instance, 1 ms, usually between 1 ms and 100 ms) in a cycling list.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] So, process A executes for 1 ms, then process B, then process C, then back to process A.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] More advanced algorithms take into account process priority, or the importance of the process.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] This allows some processes to use more time than others.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] The kernel always uses whatever resources it needs to ensure proper functioning of the system, and so can be said to have infinite priority.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] In SMP systems, processor affinity is considered to increase overall system performance, even if it may cause a process itself to run more slowly.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] This generally improves performance by reducing cache thrashing.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] IBM OS/360 was available with three different schedulers.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] Later virtual storage versions of MVS added a *Workload Manager* feature to the scheduler, which schedules processor resources according to an elaborate scheme defined by the installation.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] Very early MS-DOS and Microsoft Windows systems were non-multitasking, and as such did not feature a scheduler.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] Windows 3.1x used a non-preemptive scheduler, meaning that it did not interrupt programs.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] It relied on the program to end or tell the OS that it didn't need the processor so that it could move on to another process.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] This is usually called cooperative multitasking.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] Windows 95 introduced a rudimentary preemptive scheduler; however, for legacy support opted to let 16-bit applications run without preemption.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] Windows NT-based operating systems use a multilevel feedback queue.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] 32 priority levels are defined, 0 through 31, with priorities 0 through 15 being *normal* priorities and priorities 16 through 31 being soft real-time priorities, requiring privileges to assign.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] User interfaces and APIs work with priority classes for the process and the threads in the process, which are then combined by the system into the absolute priority level.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] The scheduler was modified in Windows Vista to use the cycle counter register of modern processors to keep track of exactly how many CPU cycles a thread has executed, rather than just using an interval-timer interrupt routine.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] Vista also uses a priority scheduler for the I/O queue so that disk defragmenters and other such programs do not interfere with foreground operations.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] Mac OS 9 uses cooperative scheduling for threads, where one process controls multiple cooperative threads, and also provides preemptive scheduling for multiprocessing tasks.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] The kernel schedules multiprocessing tasks using a preemptive scheduling algorithm.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] All Process Manager processes run within a special multiprocessing task, called the *blue task*.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] Those processes are scheduled cooperatively, using a round-robin scheduling algorithm; a process yields control of the processor to another process by explicitly calling a blocking function such as `WaitNextEvent`.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] Each process has its own copy of the Thread Manager that schedules that process's threads cooperatively; a thread yields control of the processor to another thread by calling `YieldToAnyThread` or `YieldToThread`.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] macOS uses a multilevel feedback queue, with four priority bands for threads – normal, system high priority, kernel mode only, and real-time.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] Threads are scheduled preemptively; macOS also supports cooperatively scheduled threads in its implementation of the Thread Manager in Carbon.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] Threads are primarily of interest for applications that currently consist of several asynchronous processes.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] These applications might impose a lighter load on the system if converted to a multithreaded structure.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] AIX 5 implements the following scheduling policies: FIFO, round robin, and fair round robin.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] The FIFO policy has three different implementations: FIFO, FIFO2, and FIFO3.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] The round robin policy is named SCHED_RR in AIX, and the fair round robin is called SCHED_OTHER.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] Linux 1.2 used a round-robin scheduling policy.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] Linux 2.2 added scheduling classes and support for symmetric multiprocessing (SMP).
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] In Linux 2.4, an O(n) scheduler with a multilevel feedback queue with priority levels ranging from 0 to 140 was used; 0–99 are reserved for real-time tasks and 100–140 are considered nice task levels.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] For real-time tasks, the time quantum for switching processes was approximately 200 ms, and for nice tasks approximately 10 ms.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] The scheduler ran through the run queue of all ready processes, letting the highest priority processes go first and run through their time slices, after which they will be placed in an expired queue.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] When the active queue is empty, the expired queue will become the active queue and vice versa.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] However, some enterprise Linux distributions such as SUSE Linux Enterprise Server replaced this scheduler with a backport of the O(1) scheduler (which was maintained by Alan Cox in his Linux 2.4-ac Kernel series) to the Linux 2.4 kernel used by the distribution.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] In versions 2.6.0 to 2.6.22, the kernel used an O(1) scheduler developed by Ingo Molnar and many other kernel developers during the Linux 2.5 development.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] For many kernels in this time frame, Con Kolivas developed patch sets which improved interactivity with this scheduler or even replaced it with his own schedulers.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] Con Kolivas' work, most significantly his implementation of fair scheduling named Rotating Staircase Deadline (RSDL), inspired Ingo Molnár to develop the Completely Fair Scheduler (CFS) as a replacement for the earlier O(1) scheduler, crediting Kolivas in his announcement.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] CFS is the first implementation of a fair queuing process scheduler widely used in a general-purpose operating system.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] The CFS uses a well-studied, classic scheduling algorithm called fair queuing originally invented for packet networks.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] Fair queuing had been previously applied to CPU scheduling under the name stride scheduling.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] The fair queuing CFS scheduler has a scheduling complexity of $O(\log N)$ , where N is the number of tasks in the runqueue.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] Choosing a task can be done in constant time, but reinserting a task after it has run requires $O(\log N)$ operations, because the run queue is implemented as a red–black tree.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] The Brain Fuck Scheduler, also created by Con Kolivas, is an alternative to the CFS.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] In 2023, Peter Zijlstra proposed replacing CFS with an earliest eligible virtual deadline first scheduling (EEVDF) process scheduler.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] The aim was to remove the need for CFS *latency nice* patches.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] Linux 6.12 added support for scheduler extensions that can be added from userspace; this mechanism is known as sched_ext.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] An eBPF program can be loaded into the kernel to implement a scheduling policy.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] These schedulers can replace the default scheduler.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] FreeBSD uses a multilevel feedback queue with priorities ranging from 0–255.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] 0–63 are reserved for interrupts, 64–127 for the top half of the kernel, 128–159 for real-time user threads, 160–223 for time-shared user threads, and 224–255 for idle user threads.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] Also, like Linux, it uses the active queue setup, but it also has an idle queue.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] NetBSD uses a multilevel feedback queue with priorities ranging from 0–223.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] 0–63 are reserved for time-shared threads (default, SCHED_OTHER policy), 64–95 for user threads that entered kernel space, 96–128 for kernel threads, 128–191 for user real-time threads (SCHED_FIFO and SCHED_RR policies), and 192–223 for software interrupts.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] Solaris uses a multilevel feedback queue with priorities ranging between 0 and 169.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] Priorities 0–59 are reserved for time-shared threads, 60–99 for system threads, 100–159 for real-time threads, and 160–169 for low priority interrupts.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] Unlike Linux, when a process is done using its time quantum, it is given a new priority and put back in the queue.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] Solaris 9 introduced two new scheduling classes, namely fixed-priority class and fair share class.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] The threads with fixed priority have the same priority range as that of the time-sharing class, but their priorities are not dynamically adjusted.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] The fair scheduling class uses CPU *shares* to prioritize threads for scheduling decisions.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] CPU shares indicate the entitlement to CPU resources.
[src:real-time-linux-preempt/scheduling-computing] They are allocated to a set of processes, which are collectively known as a project.
